0 July 1403":"30 juli 1403","1403":"1403","1414":"1414","1358":"1358","1313":"1313","1445":"1445","1332":"1332","1353":"1353","1419":"1419","Crewe, Cheshire, England":"Crewe, Cheshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Shipbrook, Cheshire, England":"Shipbrook, Cheshire, England","Shipbrook, Northwich, Cheshire, England":"Shipbrook, Cheshire, England","Losterk, Cheshire, Eng.":"Cheshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Shrewsbury, Shropshire, England":"Shrewsbury, Shropshire, England"},"en":{"1353–30 July 1403":"1353–30 July 1403","1332–1414":"1332–1414","1353–1403":"1353–1403","1358–1445":"1358–1445","1383–1419":"1383–1419","1390–Male":"1390–Deceased","1305–1396":"1305–1396","1313–Female":"1313–Deceased","1396":"1396","1383":"1383","1382":"1382","1390":"1390","1305":"1305","30 July 1403":"30 July 1403","1403":"1403","1414":"1414","1358":"1358","1313":"1313","1445":"1445","1332":"1332","1353":"1353","1419":"1419","Crewe, Cheshire, England":"Crewe, Cheshire, England, United Kingdom","Shipbrook, Cheshire, England":"Shipbrook, Cheshire, England","Shipbrook, Northwich, Cheshire, England":"Shipbrook, Cheshire, England","Losterk, Cheshire, Eng.":"Cheshire, England, United Kingdom","Shrewsbury, Shropshire, England":"Shrewsbury, Shropshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Vernon","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): habitational name from Vernon in Eure, France, named from the Gaulish element <i>ver(n)</i> ‘alder’ + the Gallo-Roman locative suffix <i>-o</i> (genitive <i>-ōnis</i>).","French: habitational name from the same place as in 1 above or from any of several other places in France with the same name and etymology."],"variants":[{"name":"Varnon","meanings":["English (Leicestershire and Northamptonshire): variant of   Vernon  ."]}]},{"name":"Richard","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."],"variants":[{"name":"Rikert","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."]},{"name":"Rickert","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705195,"age":29,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Sir Richard de Vernon was born in 1353, in Shipbrook, Cheshire, England, his father, Lord Richard de Vernon, was 11350 and his mother, Elizabeth Dokinfield, was 40. He married Isabel de Malbank in 1382, in Crewe, Cheshire, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 2 sons. He died on 30 July 1403, in Shrewsbury, Shropshire, England, at the age of 50."},"et":{"1353–30 July 1403":"1353–30. juuli 1403","1332–1414":"1332–1414","1353–1403":"1353–1403","1358–1445":"1358–1445","1383–1419":"1383–1419","1390–Male":"1390–Surnud","1305–1396":"1305–1396","1313–Female":"1313–Surnud","1396":"1396","1383":"1383","1382":"1382","1390":"1390","1305":"1305","30 July 1403":"30. juuli 1403","1403":"1403","1414":"1414","1358":"1358","1313":"1313","1445":"1445","1332":"1332","1353":"1353","1419":"1419","Crewe, Cheshire, England":"Crewe, Cheshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Shipbrook, Cheshire, England":"Shipbrook, Cheshire, England","Shipbrook, Northwich, Cheshire, England":"Shipbrook, Cheshire, England","Losterk, Cheshire, Eng.":"Cheshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Shrewsbury, Shropshire, England":"Shrewsbury, Shropshire, England"},"fi":{"1353–30 July 1403":"1353–30. heinäkuuta 1403","1332–1414":"1332–1414","1353–1403":"1353–1403","1358–1445":"1358–1445","1383–1419":"1383–1419","1390–Male":"1390–Kuollut","1305–1396":"1305–1396","1313–Female":"1313–Kuollut","1396":"1396","1383":"1383","1382":"